723091f-a.text:
Rutherford Place at the N.W. corner of East 16th Street, showing St. Georges P.E. Church as photographed westward across the westerly half of Stuyvesant Park. The photogranhers vantage point is Second Avenue at 16th Street. Note the open latticed spires atop the church. These became weakened by fire anc were removed (prior to 1890).
About 1871

723092f-a.text:
Rutherford Place, at the N. W. corner of East 16th Street, showing St. Georges P. E. Church. This edifice erected in 1845, replaced the first church, a chapel of Trinity at Beekman and Cliff Street's. The latter was erected in 1752 and was known as the "Swamp Church". The sharp peek of the Memorial House (erected in 1885, the gift of J. P. Morgan, a communicant) appears at the left margin. The photographer is viewing westward from a point in the west half of Stuyvesant Park.
May 17, 1892
Gift of Urbrock Collection

711350f-a.text:
East 16th Street, at the N.W. corner of Rutherford Place (extreme right, front facing there upon), showing the side of St. George's P.E. Church. The tree seen is at the rear of the same and in front of the Rectory, which, being set back from the curb, does not appear. At the extreme left is a portion of St. George's Memorial House. The photographer is viewing eastward from a point slightly east of Third Ave.

July 13, 1929

P.L. Sperr

711351f-a.text:
East 16th Street, north side, west from Rutherford Place, showing adjoining the N.E. corner of Third Ave. (Elevated line thereon), St. Georges Memorial House, erected by J.P. Morgan, a parishioner at this church. Between this and the Church (right, rear shown) is the Rectory, a 3-story stone structure that is set back from the normal building line and therefor obscured. To the west of Third Ave. is shown the new annex to Washington Irving High School under construction.
February 5, 1938.
George D. Chinn.

711352f-a.text:
209 East 16th Street, north side, between Rutherford Place and Third Ave., showing the Rectory of St. Georges P.E. Church between St. Georges Memorial House (left) and the rear of the Church (right).
February 5, 1938.
George D. Chinn.
